                        <h5>How to Practice Forest Bathing</h5>
                        <p>Unlike hiking or other goal-oriented activities, forest bathing is about slowing down and being present:</p>
                        <ul class="mb-4">
                            <li>Find a quiet forest or wooded area away from urban noise</li>
                            <li>Leave your devices behind or switch them to silent mode</li>
                            <li>Walk slowly, without a specific destination</li>
                            <li>Breathe deeply and engage all your senses</li>
                            <li>Notice the smell of the trees, the sound of birds, the feel of the ground beneath your feet</li>
                            <li>Sit quietly for at least 20 minutes to fully absorb the forest atmosphere</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h5>Incorporating Forest Time Into Your Routine</h5>
                        <p>Even if you live in an urban environment, you can benefit from regular contact with trees. A weekly visit to a local park with mature trees, or monthly trips to nearby nature reserves can significantly impact your health. Start with just 20 minutes twice a week and gradually increase your forest time as you begin to notice the benefits.</p>

                        <p>Remember, consistency matters more than duration. Regular brief encounters with nature are more beneficial than occasional lengthy excursions.</p>

